---
/**
 * /distribution — Entanglement distribution
 *
 * Tier C · Mechanisms.
 *
 * Distribution is the operation of placing one half of an entangled pair
 * at each of two distant nodes across a single link. Three architectures
 * (MeetInTheMiddle, SenderReceiver, MidpointSource) span essentially every
 * quantum-network experiment to date — Jones et al. NJP 18 083015 (2016).
 *
 * Citations:
 *   - jones-njp-2016 — canonical 3-architecture taxonomy.
 *   - pompili-science-2021 — three-node NV demo (MeetInTheMiddle), QuTech 7m intra-lab.
 *   - kumar-ijndc-2025 — current network survey, default reference.
 *   - kozlowski-rfc9340 — link-layer service contract.
 */
import Infographic from "../layouts/Infographic.astro";
import Center from "../components/Center.astro";
import Stack from "../components/Stack.astro";
import SiteNav from "../components/SiteNav.astro";
import SourceNote from "../components/SourceNote.astro";
import Grid from "../components/Grid.astro";
import Callout from "../components/Callout.astro";

const sections = [
  { id: "overview",     label: "Overview" },
  { id: "architectures", label: "Three architectures" },
  { id: "tradeoff",     label: "Rate-vs-loss trade-off" },
  { id: "timing",       label: "Heralding and timing" },
  { id: "multiplexing", label: "Multiplexing" },
  { id: "role",         label: "Network role" },
];
---

<Infographic
  title="Entanglement distribution"
  description="Distribution is how one half of a generated entangled pair ends up at each of two distant nodes across a single link. Three architectures dominate (Jones et al. NJP 18 083015, 2016): MeetInTheMiddle, SenderReceiver, MidpointSource. They differ in where the entangled-photon source sits and who runs the Bell-state analyser, and they trade rate against photon loss differently. Chained with entanglement swapping, distribution gives multi-hop reach."
  references={[
    "jones-njp-2016",
    "kozlowski-rfc9340",
    "kumar-ijndc-2025",
    "pompili-science-2021",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="distribution" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>Entanglement distribution</h1>
        <p>
          Generating an entangled pair is a local physics question. Distributing one —
          placing one half at each of two distant nodes — is a network-design question
          with several distinct architectural answers. Three architectures span
          essentially every quantum-network experiment to date, distinguished by where
          the entangled-photon source sits and who runs the Bell-state
          analyser <SourceNote id="jones-njp-2016" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          Distribution is the single-link half of the link-layer service: the network's
          contract is to deliver a Bell pair on demand between two adjacent nodes, with
          a stated fidelity and rate <SourceNote id="kozlowski-rfc9340" />. Above one
          link, distribution composes with entanglement swapping at intermediate relays
          to give multi-hop reach (covered in the swapping and repeaters subjects).
          Below distribution sit the device-level questions of how the pair is generated
          in the first place — orthogonal to the architectural axis covered here.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section id="architectures" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Three architectures</h2>
        <p>
          The taxonomy is due to Jones et al. (2016), who set out three single-link
          architectures and analysed their rates as a function of loss and memory
          parameters. The architectures differ along two related axes — where the
          entangled-photon source sits, and which node holds the Bell-state analyser —
          and that choice fixes nearly every other engineering trade-off on the
          link <SourceNote id="jones-njp-2016" />.
        </p>

        <Grid min="18rem" gap="var(--space-3)">
          <article class="arch-card">
            <h3>MeetInTheMiddle (MM)</h3>
            <p>
              Each of the two repeater nodes generates a matter-photon entangled pair
              locally and sends its photon toward the link midpoint. The two photons
              interfere on a beam splitter at a midpoint Bell-state analyser; a
              successful coincidence detection erases which-node-emitted-which
              information and heralds an entangled pair between the two matter qubits.
              The arrangement behind most current solid-state and ion-trap
              remote-entanglement experiments <SourceNote id="pompili-science-2021" />.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="arch-card">
            <h3>SenderReceiver (SR)</h3>
            <p>
              The sender (Alice) generates a matter-photon pair and sends its photon
              all the way to the receiver (Bob), who interferes it with a photon
              entangled with his own memory and runs the Bell-state analyser at his
              end. Memory qubits are needed only at the receiver; the sender re-tries
              if a photon is lost. Simpler hardware than MM, but more sensitive to
              round-trip loss because the photon traverses the full link rather than
              half <SourceNote id="jones-njp-2016" />.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="arch-card">
            <h3>MidpointSource (MS)</h3>
            <p>
              An entangled-pair source sits at the midpoint and emits one photon
              outward toward each of the two endpoints, where each is captured by a
              memory. Heralding here is on the source-side detection of the partner
              photon, which is more robust to photon loss than two-photon interference
              at distance — MS achieves higher rates than MM or SR when loss is high.
              SPDC is the natural device choice for the midpoint
              source <SourceNote id="jones-njp-2016" />.
            </p>
          </article>
        </Grid>

        <p>
          Schematic comparison of the three architectures, after Jones et al.
          <em>New J. Phys.</em> 18 083015 (2016) <SourceNote id="jones-njp-2016" />.
          Filled circles are matter qubits (memories); the dashed accent box is the
          Bell-state analyser; the accent-bordered diamond is an entangled-pair source.
          MM and MS both place equipment at the link midpoint but use it differently:
          MM measures (heralds on two-photon interference); MS emits (heralds on a
          single source-side detection). SR runs no midpoint equipment and places the
          BSA at the receiver.
        </p>

        <figure class="arch-fig">
          <div class="arch-fig-scroll">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 720 100" role="img"
               aria-label="MeetInTheMiddle: photons from each endpoint travel to a midpoint Bell-state analyser">
            <text x="20" y="30" class="arch-row-label">MM</text>
            <rect x="60" y="10" width="80" height="50" rx="4"
                  fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <circle cx="85" cy="35" r="8" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <text x="85" y="76" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-node-label">Alice memory</text>
            <line x1="145" y1="35" x2="295" y2="35" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"
                  marker-end="url(#arrow-mm)"/>
            <rect x="300" y="10" width="120" height="50" rx="4"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
            <text x="360" y="40" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-bsa-label">BSA</text>
            <text x="360" y="76" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-node-label">midpoint analyser</text>
            <line x1="575" y1="35" x2="425" y2="35" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"
                  marker-end="url(#arrow-mm)"/>
            <rect x="580" y="10" width="80" height="50" rx="4"
                  fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <circle cx="635" cy="35" r="8" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <text x="635" y="76" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-node-label">Bob memory</text>
            <defs>
              <marker id="arrow-mm" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5"
                      markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
                <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
              </marker>
            </defs>
          </svg>
          </div>
          <figcaption><strong>MeetInTheMiddle.</strong> Both endpoints emit photons toward a midpoint BSA. Heralding requires two-photon interference; rate scales with full-link transmission.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="arch-fig">
          <div class="arch-fig-scroll">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 720 100" role="img"
               aria-label="SenderReceiver: photon travels the full link from sender to receiver who runs the analyser">
            <text x="20" y="30" class="arch-row-label">SR</text>
            <rect x="60" y="10" width="80" height="50" rx="4"
                  fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <circle cx="85" cy="35" r="8" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <text x="85" y="76" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-node-label">Alice memory</text>
            <line x1="145" y1="35" x2="555" y2="35" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"
                  marker-end="url(#arrow-sr)"/>
            <rect x="560" y="10" width="100" height="50" rx="4"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-accent)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
            <circle cx="585" cy="35" r="8" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <text x="625" y="40" class="arch-bsa-label">BSA</text>
            <text x="610" y="76" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-node-label">Bob memory + analyser</text>
            <defs>
              <marker id="arrow-sr" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5"
                      markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
                <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
              </marker>
            </defs>
          </svg>
          </div>
          <figcaption><strong>SenderReceiver.</strong> Sender's photon traverses the full link; receiver runs the BSA. Single-photon transmission, but the photon travels the entire distance.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <figure class="arch-fig">
          <div class="arch-fig-scroll">
          <svg viewBox="0 0 720 100" role="img"
               aria-label="MidpointSource: an entangled pair source at the midpoint emits one photon to each endpoint">
            <text x="20" y="30" class="arch-row-label">MS</text>
            <rect x="60" y="10" width="80" height="50" rx="4"
                  fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <circle cx="85" cy="35" r="8" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <text x="85" y="76" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-node-label">Alice memory</text>
            <polygon points="360,10 420,35 360,60 300,35"
                     fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-accent)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <text x="360" y="40" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-bsa-label">SPDC</text>
            <text x="360" y="76" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-node-label">midpoint pair source</text>
            <line x1="300" y1="35" x2="145" y2="35" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"
                  marker-end="url(#arrow-ms)"/>
            <line x1="420" y1="35" x2="575" y2="35" stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.2"
                  marker-end="url(#arrow-ms)"/>
            <rect x="580" y="10" width="80" height="50" rx="4"
                  fill="var(--color-surface-2)" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"/>
            <circle cx="635" cy="35" r="8" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
            <text x="635" y="76" text-anchor="middle" class="arch-node-label">Bob memory</text>
            <defs>
              <marker id="arrow-ms" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5"
                      markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto-start-reverse">
                <path d="M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z" fill="var(--color-text)"/>
              </marker>
            </defs>
          </svg>
          </div>
          <figcaption><strong>MidpointSource.</strong> A pair source at the midpoint emits one photon to each endpoint. Heralding fires on the source-side partner; no two-photon interference required.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section id="tradeoff" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Rate-vs-loss trade-off</h2>
        <p>
          The three architectures put their photons through different amounts of fibre,
          and they condition success on different events. That fixes the loss scaling.
          Per attempted heralding event, the success probability scales roughly as
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>MM</strong> — both photons must survive a half-link and interfere,
            so the rate scales with the square of the half-link transmission, i.e.
            with full-link transmission.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>SR</strong> — the sender's photon must survive the full link;
            single-photon transmission, but the photon travels the entire distance.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>MS</strong> — heralding fires when the source-side partner photon
            is detected locally, so the heralding rate is independent of the link loss
            on the photon that actually reaches the memory. Loss still kills the
            <em>useful</em> rate (the photon has to arrive at the memory to be
            captured), but the architecture sidesteps the two-photon-interference
            requirement.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          At low loss MM and SR are competitive and MM's symmetry tends to win on
          fidelity; at high loss MS dominates because heralding doesn't require
          two-photon interference at distance. Jones et al. work the simulations out
          in detail and identify the regime crossovers as a function of fibre length,
          memory coherence, and source-clock rate <SourceNote id="jones-njp-2016" />.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section id="timing" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Heralding and timing</h2>
        <p>
          Heralding — a classical signal back to each memory-holding node announcing
          "your photon was successfully detected at the analyser" — is what turns a
          probabilistic distribution attempt into a deterministic resource. Two timing
          constraints apply.
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Coherence budget.</strong> The heralding signal must travel back
            to the memory-holding node before the memory's coherence runs out. For MM
            and MS this round-trip is one full link time — the memory must hold its
            qubit through generation, photon emission, propagation to the midpoint,
            detection, and the classical herald back. For SR the BSA sits at the
            receiver, so the receiver's memory only needs to span its local
            generation-plus-detection; the sender does not need a memory at all and
            simply re-tries. This is what makes SR attractive when memory coherence
            is the binding constraint.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Source-clock rate.</strong> The source has to fire fast enough that
            within one coherence time the link gets enough heralding attempts for at
            least one to succeed. For MM and MS this sets a clock-rate target as a
            function of loss; for MS specifically, fast SPDC clocks plus single-photon
            detection give the architecture its high-loss advantage.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="multiplexing" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Multiplexing</h2>
        <p>
          All three architectures are independently composable with multiplexing —
          running multiple heralding attempts in parallel along axes the link can
          separate. Three modalities are standard:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Time-bin multiplexing.</strong> The source fires in many
            distinguishable time slots within one coherence window; the BSA sees them
            as independent attempts.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Frequency-bin multiplexing.</strong> The source emits across
            several separable frequency channels, each running an independent
            heralding pipeline, often via WDM components borrowed from classical
            optics.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Memory-qubit multiplexing.</strong> Each node holds an array of
            memory qubits; multiple distribution attempts are kept in flight in
            parallel, and whichever one succeeds first is promoted to the active pair.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Multiplexing is the lever that makes long-link distribution tractable. The
          single-attempt success probability shrinks with loss; multiplexing recovers
          rate by running many attempts per coherence window. The architectural axis
          (MM / SR / MS) and the multiplexing axis (time / frequency / memory) are
          orthogonal — a real link picks one of each <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
        <Callout label="Architecture vs device — separate axes">
          <p>
            "Where the source sits and who measures" (the architecture taxonomy on
            this page) is independent of "what hardware emits the photon" (SPDC, NV
            centre, trapped ion, quantum dot, etc.). The same MS architecture can run
            with an SPDC source at the midpoint or with a quantum-dot source; the same
            quantum-dot device can serve as the local source in MM or as the midpoint
            source in MS. Conflating the two axes — e.g. equating "MidpointSource"
            with "SPDC" — produces silently-wrong rate and fidelity claims.
          </p>
        </Callout>
      </section>

      <section id="role" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Network role</h2>
        <p>
          Distribution is the operation that makes the link-layer service contract
          true <SourceNote id="kozlowski-rfc9340" />: given a request for a Bell pair
          between two adjacent nodes, the link runs whatever architecture it is built
          around (MM, SR, or MS) and delivers a heralded pair at the contracted
          fidelity and rate. Distribution is the implementation that satisfies the
          contract on a single link.
        </p>
        <p>
          Three follow-on subjects build on distribution:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Repeaters</strong> integrate distribution and swapping into the
            1G / 2G / 3G architectural families and analyse end-to-end rate-vs-loss
            scaling. <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>repeaters</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Links</strong> looks at the physical-layer side: fibre,
            hollow-core fibre, free-space, and satellite media, and what each costs in
            attenuation and latency. <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>links</strong>
            <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Metrics</strong> defines loss, decoherence, and fidelity
            quantitatively — the inputs the rate-vs-loss curves on this page consume.
            <em>Covered in the</em> <strong>metrics</strong> <em>subject.</em>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </Stack>
  </Center>
</Infographic>

